response:
I have the complete picture. Here is the full diagnosis, fix, and codification.

---

## Diagnosis

The bug lives in **`src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`** — specifically the `.siteWrapper` rule. Even though the content-only `min-width` guard exists correctly on `.contentAreaInner`, there is a second, unguarded `min-width` on `.siteWrapper` itself (or on `body`/`html` in globals) that creates a floor at the document root level. When a `min-width` is set on a **flex column root that also contains `position: sticky` navigation**, the browser expands the entire stacking context to that floor. On any viewport narrower than that floor, the document never gets wider than the floor value, `overflow-x` on the document root is `visible` by default (not `auto`), and the sticky nav stretches with the document — so its right edge is clipped outside the viewport. Because the document itself has been widened, the browser suppresses horizontal scroll on the page root.

## Root Cause — **AP-067**

> **AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome**

The pattern is: a `min-width` floor (or an equivalent `min-width` from a misapplied content rule) placed on `.siteWrapper`, `body`, `html`, or any ancestor that contains the nav and footer. The floor **expands the document root**, which causes two simultaneous failures:
1. `position: sticky` nav stretches to the inflated document width → right items are off-screen.
2. The browser does not add a horizontal scrollbar to the page root because the root element's own box *fits* the viewport — the overflow is positional, not box-overflow. So the user has no way to scroll to the clipped items.

The correct architecture (already described in `responsive.md §6.10` and implemented on `.contentAreaInner`) is: **the floor lives only on the content inner wrapper**, and the scroll container is the `.contentArea` parent, which is a sibling of — never an ancestor of — functional chrome (nav, footer).

## The Actual Offending Code

Looking at `layout.module.scss`, the `.siteWrapper` is clean:

```scss
.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  // ← no min-width here ✓
}
```

But the `@media` block sets `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` — this is correct. The problem is that **`.siteWrapper` has no `overflow-x: clip` or `max-width: 100vw` guard**, so if any child overflows the wrapper (e.g. the `.navInner` has `max-width: $elan-container-wide` = 1440px and no `min-width`, but the `padding` plus the nav links at sub-320px may force intrinsic minimum content width above the viewport), the *document* body stretches to accommodate the nav's intrinsic minimum — and the root never scrolls.

The specific mechanism: at <320px, the `.navInner`'s flex layout has `.logo` (`flex-shrink: 0`, `white-space: nowrap`) and `.links` with several link items. The logo's `white-space: nowrap` + `flex-shrink: 0` + the links' minimum content widths together produce an intrinsic minimum width for `.navInner` of ~280–320px. Since `.siteWrapper` is `display: flex; flex-direction: column` with no `overflow: clip` and no `min-width: 0`, it expands to that minimum. The *document* expands. The page has no horizontal scroll. Nav items on the right are unreachable.

## Fix

Three coordinated changes:

### 1. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`

Add `overflow-x: clip` to `.siteWrapper` to seal the document root against any nav/footer overflow, and add `min-width: 0` to prevent flex blowout. The nav and footer must handle their own narrow-viewport layouts internally (which they already do via `$elan-mq-sm`).

```scss
.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;

  // ── DOCUMENT-ROOT OVERFLOW SEAL ──────────────────────────────────────────
  // Prevents any child (nav, footer, content) from inflating the document
  // root width. Without this, a sticky nav with nowrap text or a content
  // div with a min-width floor can expand `body` past the viewport — the
  // browser then suppresses horizontal scrollbar on the root (because the
  // root box technically fits), so clipped nav items become unreachable.
  // `clip` (not `hidden`) is used because `hidden` creates a scroll container
  // that breaks `position: sticky` on the nav. See AP-067, AP-073, FB-151.
  overflow-x: clip;
  // Prevent this flex column from blowing out past its containing block.
  min-width: 0;

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  // … all existing radius overrides unchanged …
```

> **Why `clip` not `hidden`?** `overflow: hidden` on an ancestor **creates a new scroll container**, which breaks `position: sticky` — the sticky element sticks to the nearest scroll container, not the viewport. `overflow-x: clip` clips without creating a scroll container (it is not a scroll container per CSS spec), so sticky positioning is preserved. This is a critical distinction. See AP-013.

### 2. `src/app/globals.scss`

Add a document-level seal on `html` and `body` so that no layout path — including future route groups — can accidentally allow horizontal document growth:

```scss
@layer base {
  *,
  *::before,
  *::after {
    box-sizing: border-box;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  html {
    font-size: 16px;
    -webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;
    scroll-behavior: smooth;
    // Prevent any child from inflating the document beyond the viewport.
    // `clip` does not create a scroll container so sticky nav is unaffected.
    // See AP-073.
    overflow-x: clip;
  }

  body {
    font-family: var(--portfolio-font-sans);
    font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-regular);
    line-height: var(--portfolio-leading-normal);
    color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
    background: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-minimal);
    -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
    -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
    // Belt-and-suspenders: body also sealed, min-width: 0 prevents flex blowout
    // if body is ever placed in a flex/grid context.
    overflow-x: clip;
    min-width: 0;
  }
```

### 3. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

The `.navInner` already has `max-width` and padding. At sub-320px the flex row's intrinsic minimum width must not blow out the nav. Add `min-width: 0` to `.navInner` and ensure the links list can compress:

```scss
.navInner {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  max-width: $elan-container-wide;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-2x);
  // At sub-320px viewports, prevent this flex row from inflating past the
  // viewport. Combined with overflow-x: clip on .siteWrapper, nav items
  // that don't fit at extreme narrow widths are clipped — NOT unreachable
  // (the document does not expand, so no phantom scroll zone is created).
  min-width: 0;
  width: 100%;

  @media #{$elan-mq-sm} {
    padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-4x);
  }
}
```

---

## New Anti-Pattern to Codify — AP-073

Add to **`docs/design-anti-patterns.md`** (Spacing & Layout category):

```markdown
<a id="ap-073"></a>
## AP-073: `overflow-x: hidden` (or no overflow seal) on the Document Root Containing Sticky Nav

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger:** Setting `min-width` on `.siteWrapper`, `body`, or `html` — or setting
`overflow-x: hidden` on any ancestor that wraps a `position: sticky` element — at
any level above the scroll-contained content region.

**Why it's wrong:** Two distinct failure modes depending on the property used:

1. **No overflow seal (`min-width` on root, no `overflow-x`):** A sticky nav's
   `white-space: nowrap` logo or flex minimum content width inflates the document
   root past the viewport width. The browser does not add a horizontal scrollbar
   to the page root (because the root element's box fits — only the content
   overflows positionally). At viewports narrower than the nav's intrinsic
   minimum, items on the right side of the nav are clipped and unreachable.
   Hovering reveals them but they cannot be scrolled to. See FB-151.

2. **`overflow: hidden` on root:** Creates a scroll container. `position: sticky`
   sticks to that container instead of the viewport. The nav scrolls with the page
   and loses its sticky behavior entirely. See AP-013.

**Correct alternative:**
```css
/* html / body / .siteWrapper */
overflow-x: clip;   /* clips without creating a scroll container */
min-width: 0;       /* prevents flex blowout */
```

`overflow-x: clip` is the only value that (a) prevents document-root horizontal
inflation and (b) does not create a scroll container, preserving `position: sticky`
on all descendants.

**The min-width floor rule:** A `min-width` floor for "prevent mobile layout at
narrow desktop viewports" must **only** be placed on an inner content wrapper
(`.contentAreaInner`) whose direct parent is an `overflow-x: auto` scroll
container (`.contentArea`). That scroll container must be a **sibling** of the
nav and footer, never their ancestor. Placing the floor anywhere above the
scroll container boundary — including on `.siteWrapper`, `body`, or `html` —
violates this rule. See `docs/design/responsive.md §6.10`.

**Frustration caused:** 1 round — at sub-320px viewports, nav items were clipped
on the right and unreachable because the document root expanded to the nav's
intrinsic minimum width but suppressed horizontal scroll.

**Related:** AP-013 (fixed positioning inside transformed containers), FB-147,
FB-149, FB-151.
```

